Instead of using the `Mono::cast` to change the type of the Mono, this can be solved by specifying the type of the `Mono.error` using a bit of Java generic magic in the form of `Mono.&lt;User&gt;error(...)`.  This has the additional advantage that you do not need to alter the flow of the Mono pipeline by adding logic to the `flatMap` method with null handling but never actually receiving a null.

