Instead of going back and forth in the comments, I verified your problem and the solution, so here is a more detailed explanation.

I copied your code and removed the bits that are irrelevant for your usecase.
Since you&#39;re using Dynamic Email Templates and persionalizations, I removed the following:

- I removed `To` from the `Mail` since it&#39;ll be provided by the personalization
- I removed the plain text and HTML content, since the content will be provided by the Dynamic Email Template.
- I removed the `Subject` from the `Mail` and `Personalization` since it&#39;ll be provided by the Dynamics Email Template.

This is what the code looks like now:

```java
package org.example;

import com.sendgrid.Method;
import com.sendgrid.Request;
import com.sendgrid.Response;
import com.sendgrid.SendGrid;
import com.sendgrid.helpers.mail.Mail;
import com.sendgrid.helpers.mail.objects.Email;
import com.sendgrid.helpers.mail.objects.Personalization;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            Mail mail = new Mail();
            mail.setFrom(new Email(&quot;[SENDER_EMAIL_ADDRESS]&quot;, &quot;[SENDER_NAME]&quot;));
            mail.setTemplateId(&quot;d-[YOUR_DYNAMIC_TEMPLATE_ID]&quot;);

            final Personalization personalization1 = new Personalization();
            personalization1.addTo(new Email(&quot;[RECIPIENT_EMAIL_ADDRESS]&quot;, &quot;[RECIPIENT_NAME]&quot;));
            personalization1.addDynamicTemplateData(&quot;car_name&quot;, &quot;Volkswagen Beetle&quot;);
            mail.addPersonalization(personalization1);

            SendGrid sg = new SendGrid(&quot;SG.[YOUR_SENDGRID_API_KEY}&quot;);
            Request request = new Request();
            request.setMethod(Method.POST);
            request.setEndpoint(&quot;mail/send&quot;);
            System.out.println(mail.build());
            request.setBody(mail.build());
            Response response = sg.api(request);
            System.out.println(&quot;status code: &quot; + response.getStatusCode());
            System.out.println(&quot;response body: &quot; + response.getBody());
            System.out.println(&quot;response header : &quot; + response.getHeaders());
        } catch (Exception ex) {
            System.out.println(&quot;inside exception&quot; + ex.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

I added the `car_name` Dynamic Template Data, so I can use it in the email subject of the Dynamic Email Template, [following this guidance][1].

[![Settings of a SendGrid Dynamic Email Template with subject that uses template data.][2]][2]

When I do set the subject using `mail.SetSubject` or `personalization1.setSubject`, those subjects are ignored, and the subject configured on the Dynamic Email Template is still used. Even when the subject configured on the Dynamic Email Template is empty, the `mail.subject` and `personalization.subject` are still ignored. When you&#39;re using Dynamic Email Templates, it has to be set using the subject on the Dynamic Email Template.

One workaround is to set the subject on the Dynamic Email Template to `{{subject}}` and set a dynamic template data with key `subject` and whatever subject you like:

```java
personalization1.addDynamicTemplateData(&quot;subject&quot;, &quot;Your Volkswagen Beetle Extended Car Warranty&quot;);
```

[![SendGrid Dynamic Email Template settings where subject is set to {{subject}}][3]][3]


